{
  "lesson_id": "lesson_particle_wo",
  "lesson_title": "The Direct Object Marker: Identifying the Target of Action",
  "lesson_summary": "This lesson introduces the particle を (wo), which identifies the direct object of a verb. It completes our basic understanding of how nouns interact with actions in the SOV (Subject-Object-Verb) structure.",
  "grammar_point": "particle_wo",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The particle を (wo) is a 'case marker' that identifies the noun immediately preceding it as the direct object of the verb. In logical terms, if the verb is an operation, を marks the data being operated upon.",
    "formation": "[Noun] + を + [Verb]",
    "variations": [
      "In some contexts, を can also mark a space through which movement occurs (e.g., 'walking [through] a gate')."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Unlike the particle に (ni), which marks a destination or indirect recipient, を (wo) marks the thing directly affected by the action."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "In previous lessons, we learned how 'no' links nouns and 'ni' establishes location. However, a sentence often describes an action performed on something. In Chinese, we put the object after the verb (SVO). In Classical Japanese, we place the object before the verb and tag it with 'wo' (SOV). Think of 'wo' as a logical pointer that says: 'The noun I am attached to is the target of the upcoming action.'"
    },
